article.headline: Liberty loosen Mystics' grip on No. 4 seed with victory
article.linkText: Liberty hold off Mystics to close gap for playoff bid
article.story:
WASHINGTON -- The New York Liberty got the victory they needed to preserve their chances for the last playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.

Janel McCarville scored 18 points and Shameka Christon added 12, including the go-ahead free throws with 9.8 seconds remaining, to help New York beat the Washington Mystics 73-72 Thursday night.

The Liberty (14-18), winners of two of their last three games, pulled within one-half game of the Mystics for the fourth seed. Cathrine Kraayeveld added 15 points for New York, which won three of four games from Washington to win the season series and earn the tiebreaker.

"We played with a sense of urgency and that's what we needed to do," Christon said. "I think a lot of people didn't expect us to win this game. We really didn't think about that. We just went out there and played hard."

DeLisha Milton-Jones had 21 points and Alana Beard added 19 for the Mystics (15-18). The Mystics, who jumped back into the playoff hunt despite an 0-8 start to the season, lost for the third time in four games.

"We know that we gave a huge opportunity away tonight and a lot of us probably won't sleep well tonight," said Milton-Jones who played the entire 40 minutes.

The Liberty close the regular season with two home games, against Connecticut on Friday and Chicago on Sunday.

"It was a good solid win tonight and that's all we can take from it," New York coach Pat Coyle said. "The most important thing is focusing on Connecticut and how we can beat them. We got to keep it on what's really important, the game."

If the Liberty win both remaining games, they'll earn the playoff spot. If New York splits, it'll need Washington to lose its finale.

"I been saying it all year long it is going to come down to the last game of the season," Beard said. "The three years I have been here we have never beat Connecticut and this year we have their number."

The Mystics visit the Sun on Sunday having won two of the first three meetings this season. Top-seeded and defending champion Detroit awaits the eventual fourth seed in the first round.

"There will be an arena full of people who want to see us fail and we're going to be the only ones in that building who want us to succeed," Milton-Jones said. "We are going to have put our backs together and go out swinging."

After Christon's 3-pointer pushed the Liberty's lead to 60-53 in the opening minute of the fourth quarter, the Mystics used an 11-3 run to take a one-point lead. Beard capped the run with a driving layup and the go-ahead 3 with 4:28 left.

Neither side led by more than one point until Ashley Battle made one of two free throws to give New York a 71-69 lead with 51 seconds left. Beard followed with a 3 to give Washington its final lead with 27 seconds left.

Working the ball around the perimeter, the Liberty found Christon at the top of the key and she was fouled by Monique Currie as she drove down the lane. Christon hit both free throws to give the Liberty the lead.

"This is the time to step up and hit the shots, and that's what I did," Christon said.

They Mystics then called timeout to set up the final play. After the ball was knocked out of bounds with 2.6 seconds remaining, the Mystics found Beard in the right corner, but missed the shot at the buzzer.

"I thought for sure it was in," Beard said.

McCarville scored 12 points on 6-for-6 shooting in the first half to help the Liberty, which shot 59 percent (17-for-29), take a 39-33 lead at the break. Milton-Jones, coming off a season-low two points against Connecticut, led the Mystics with 11 in the half and Nakia Sanford, who finished with 14 points, had nine points in the half.
